            <div class=3D"post-header clearfix">
                <h1>How to Tell How Old a Cat Is (and Understand Cat Years)=
</h1>
                                    <div class=3D"post-category-badge">
                                                                           =
 <a title=3D"Ask The Vet" href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com/blog/ask-the=
-vet/" class=3D"category-link">
                                <span class=3D"category-icon icon-ask-the-v=
et" role=3D"img" aria-hidden=3D"true"></span>
                                <span class=3D"category-title">Ask The Vet<=
/span>
                            </a>
                                                                           =
                         <a title=3D"Cat Tips" href=3D"https://www.litter-r=
obot.com/blog/cat-tips/" class=3D"category-link">
                                <span class=3D"category-icon icon-cat-tips"=
 role=3D"img" aria-hidden=3D"true"></span>
                                <span class=3D"category-title">Cat Tips</sp=
an>
                            </a>
                                                                           =
                         <a title=3D"Cat Facts" href=3D"https://www.litter-=
robot.com/blog/cat-facts/" class=3D"category-link">
                                <span class=3D"category-icon icon-cat-facts=
" role=3D"img" aria-hidden=3D"true"></span>
                                <span class=3D"category-title">Cat Facts</s=
pan>
                            </a>
                                                                    </div>
                            </div>
            <div class=3D"post-read-time">Est. read time: 9 min.</div>
        </div>
        <div class=3D"post-content">
            <div class=3D"post-description clearfix">
                <div class=3D"post-text-hld">
                    <p>Your fur baby will inevitably undergo some changes a=
s they age. But if you weren=E2=80=99t there at birth, you might be wonderi=
ng,&nbsp;<em data-start=3D"527" data-end=3D"547">how old is my cat?</em> Un=
derstanding <strong data-start=3D"562" data-end=3D"575">cat years</strong> =
and how to tell how old a cat is can help you care for them at every stage =
of life. Let=E2=80=99s explore some tips on how to determine your cat's age=
. With recent increases in pet adoption, many pet parents might not know th=
e age of their new kitty. Learning about a cat=E2=80=99s life stages can he=
lp you make a more accurate guess at your cat's age.&nbsp;</p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h2 id=3D"h-stages-of-a-cat-s-life">Cat life stages</h2>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">There are a total of <strong>4 stages<=
/strong> of a cat's life. The stages include the following age ranges with =
some variation amongst professionals:&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:list --></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Kitten</strong>: Birth - 6 months</li>
<li><strong>Adolescent cat</strong>:&nbsp; 7 months - 2 years&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Mature cat</strong>: 3 - 10 years&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Senior/geriatric cat</strong>: 10+ years&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
<h3 dir=3D"ltr">How can you tell how old a kitten Is?</h3>
<p dir=3D"ltr">Check if teeth are present: none (0=E2=80=932 weeks), baby t=
eeth (3=E2=80=936 weeks), adult teeth (3=E2=80=936 months)p</p>
<p dir=3D"ltr">Eye color: All kittens have blue eyes at birth; they change =
around 6=E2=80=937 weeks</p>
<p dir=3D"ltr">Mobility: Kittens start walking at ~3 weeks and get playful =
by 6=E2=80=938 weeks</p>
<p dir=3D"ltr">Size: Tiny and lightweight until 4 months old</p>
<p><!-- /wp:list --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h2 id=3D"h-lifespan-of-house-cat-vs-feral-cat">Lifespan of a house cat vs =
a feral cat</h2>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>Did you know there is a major average <a href=3D"https://www.litter-robo=
t.com/blog/how-long-do-cats-live/">lifespan difference</a> between indoor h=
ouse cats and outdoor feral cats? Feral cats usually live just 2=E2=80=935 =
years due to harsh conditions like traffic, extreme weather, predators, lim=
ited diets, and no veterinary care. House cats enjoy stable food and safer =
environments but may face issues like weight gain, which can lead to diabet=
es, mobility problems, and reduced life expectancy.</p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading --></p>
<h2 id=3D"h-how-can-you-tell-how-old-a-cat-is">How to tell how old a cat is=
</h2>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:image {"id":19764,"width":545,"height":423,"sizeSlug":"large","l=
inkDestination":"none"} --></p>
<p><!-- /wp:image --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">There are multiple ways to tell a cat'=
s age, from obvious size differences to more subtle criteria. So, how old i=
s my cat? Here are some characteristics to look for to help you estimate yo=
ur cat's age.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-body-changes">Body changes</h3>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>It is easy to tell a kitten from a cat. The cute little paws and tiny no=
ses are sure ways to recognize a kitten. As cats get older, you will notice=
 a change in their body. The body of adult cats will be a little less firm =
or less defined. As cats get older, they also tend to move less and might b=
e less playful, resulting in a few more pounds.&nbsp;</p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-skin-and-fur">Skin and fur&nbsp;</h3>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Skin and fur are also indicators of ag=
e. Kittens might have soft and smooth coats, whereas </span><strong>an olde=
r cat might have a thicker, more coarse coat</strong><span style=3D"font-we=
ight: 400;">. Younger cats like to spend a lot of time grooming their coat =
to keep it looking shiny. As a cat ages, this could change. Part of it coul=
d be a lack of interest and another part could be weight gain or even healt=
h issues. You might even notice some grey in your older cat's fur! It often=
 proves difficult to use hair coat as a factor in estimating cat age withou=
t a history because you don=E2=80=99t know if those changes are secondary t=
o trauma, a medical issue, or some other specific cause unique to that cat.=
&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-tail">Tail</h3>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://images.litter-robot.com/media/wysiw=
yg/kitten_vs_adult_cat_tail_size.jpg" alt=3D"how to tell a cat's age by the=
ir tail" width=3D"800" height=3D"500"></p>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The tail of your cat grows with them a=
nd <strong>your cat usually stops growing around 2 years old</strong>. Keep=
 an eye on their tail as a marker for how much growing they have left. Some=
 cats are born without tails, with extremely short tails, and others may lo=
se their tails due to a previous incident.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-teeth">Teeth</h3>
<p><strong><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://images.litter-robot.com/med=
ia/magefan_blog/how_to_tell_a_cat_s_age_by_teeth.jpeg" alt=3D"how to tell a=
 cat's age by teeth - signs of teeth diseases in a more senior cat" width=
=3D"800" height=3D"533"></strong></p>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>Examining their teeth is <strong>the most common way</strong> to determi=
ne a cat=E2=80=99s age. It=E2=80=99s often the best method for a more preci=
se estimate. Kittens have baby teeth that fall out as adult teeth grow in, =
usually completing the process around 6 months. <strong>Younger cats also h=
ave whiter teeth</strong>, which helps pinpoint age. As cats get older, you=
=E2=80=99ll see more wear and tartar. However, if their teeth are cleaned p=
rofessionally every 1=E2=80=932 years or brushed at home, this method becom=
es less accurate.</p>
<p>Here's how to tell a cat's age by teeth:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Kittens (0 - 6 months)</strong>: small, sharp, and clean teeth.=
 Adult teeth will start coming in around 3-4 months&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Young Adult (7 months - 2 years)</strong>: By the age of 6 mont=
hs, cats will lose their baby teeth and have their adult teeth instead. Can=
ines will be fully erupted.</li>
<li><strong>Adult (3 - 6 years)</strong>: Full set of clean and white adult=
 teeth. Minimal wear may be visible.&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Mature (7 - 10 years)</strong>: Some wear on the teeth may be v=
isible, teeth may be more yellow and there might be tartar buildup.</li>
<li><strong>Senior (11 years and older)</strong>: Teeth may show significan=
t wear, and there could be signs of dental disease, such as gingivitis or m=
issing teeth.</li>
</ul>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-eyes">Eyes</h3>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://images.litter-robot.com/media/wysiw=
yg/lilac_himalayan_cat_color.jpeg" alt=3D"determining how old your cat is f=
rom its eyes" width=3D"799" height=3D"534"></p>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Looking into the gorgeous eyes of your=
 fur baby, you might be able to see a little bit about their age. You might=
 notice that your young cat has bright, beautiful eyes. As they get older, =
their eyes can actually get cloudy. This is called <strong>nuclear sclerosi=
s</strong> and is a normal aging change that does not require treatment. Ho=
wever, not every cat's eyes cloud over; they can stay just as bright as the=
ir kitten years.&nbsp;</span></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Kittens</strong>: Young kittens have bright blue eyes that typi=
cally change color as they age.</li>
<li><strong>Adult cats</strong>: cats can have a <a href=3D"https://www.lit=
ter-robot.com/blog/cat-eye-colors/">variety of eye colors depending on thei=
r breed</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Senior cats</strong>: older cats may start to develop a cloudin=
ess in their eyes.</li>
</ul>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-hormonal-changes">Hormonal changes</h3>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">As early as 4-5 months of age, an unsp=
ayed female kitten might start <a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com/blog=
/how-long-are-cats-in-heat/">going into heat</a>. Some telltale signs to lo=
ok for are:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">territorial marking</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">mating calls</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">wanting to escape outdoors</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><a href=3D"https://www.lit=
ter-robot.com/blog/why-do-cats-spray/"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">sp=
raying</span></a></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">If your kitten is an unaltered female =
and exhibiting these behaviors, it is safe to assume that she is around 5 m=
onths old. (And that it=E2=80=99s time to get her spayed!)</span></p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-mobility-and-activity-levels">Mobility and activity levels</h3>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>Remember when your sweet kitten loved to play and hop all around? Your o=
lder cat might want to spend more time sleeping instead of bouncing from co=
unter to counter. It is still important to encourage your cat to be active.=
&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">As cats get older, they can start to d=
evelop <strong>issues with their mobility</strong>. In addition to scheduli=
ng an appointment with your veterinarian to get recommendations for supplem=
ents and possible medications to keep your aging cat as youthful as possibl=
e, a </span><a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com/cat-tower.html"><span s=
tyle=3D"font-weight: 400;">cat tower</span></a> <span style=3D"font-weight:=
 400;">can encourage movement by providing multiple levels and climbing hol=
es (while also being a stylish addition to your home). This tower can keep =
cats of all ages and activity levels interested and entertained. </span></p=
>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading {"level":3} --></p>
<h3 id=3D"h-weight-gain">Weight gain</h3>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Encouraging activity and exercise also=
 helps combat cat weight gain. This might be a way to determine the age of =
your cat because older cats tend to carry more weight. As your cat gets old=
er, they might choose to be less active and move a little slower. Your cat =
might prefer eating and lounging. Though you want to ensure they are eating=
 the recommended amount, you might also want to be mindful of their intake =
based on age and weight. The </span><a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com=
/feeder-robot.html"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Feeder-Robot </span><=
/a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">allows you to customize your cat's foo=
d portions via the <a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com/the-app.html?srs=
ltid=3DAfmBOopf0_kEfuQDi6kb08RG6-Qeu10ViIAsXmt69tqfCwc75o9uTQYG">Whisker ap=
p</a>. This can help with controlling and monitoring your cat's food intake=
.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Weight gain can also indicate a medica=
l issue that needs to be addressed with your veterinarian. Regardless, 1-3 =
extra pounds on a cat is multiplied by 10 and then some in humans, so it is=
 essential to get their weight back down to prevent undue stress on their j=
oints. </span></p>
<h3 class=3D"schema-faq-section"><strong class=3D"schema-faq-question">Can =
you tell how old a cat is by its whiskers?</strong></h3>
<p class=3D"schema-faq-answer">No, your cat's whiskers do not change as the=
y age.</p>
<h3 id=3D"faq-question-1638982147000" class=3D"schema-faq-section"></h3>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading --></p>
<h2 id=3D"h-is-it-normal-for-my-cat-to-live-beyond-15-years-old">Is it norm=
al for my cat to live beyond 15 years old?</h2>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com/blog/how-long-do-cats-live/"=
>average life expectancy</a> for an indoor cat is 10-15 years, but some cat=
s live to age 20 or beyond! Keep in mind, 15 cat years is about 76 years ol=
d <a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com/blog/how-to-convert-your-cats-age=
-to-human-years/">in human years</a>. Your cat might live beyond 15 years b=
ut it will depend on their environment, breed, and overall health.</p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>You can help your cat achieve maximum life expectancy by providing them =
with great nutrition, exercise, regular vet appointments, and lots of love.=
</p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading --></p>
<h2 id=3D"h-how-can-i-take-care-of-an-aging-cat">How can I take care of an =
aging cat?</h2>
<p>Taking care of an aging cat involves addressing various aspects of their=
 health and well-being. Here are some general guidelines for caring for an =
aging cat:</p>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:list --></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Vet check-ups</strong>. Stay on top of vet appointments (twice =
yearly is recommended for senior cats)&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Accessibility</strong>. Make sure their food, water, and litter=
 box is easily accessible.&nbsp;Consider adding ramps or steps for climbing=
 onto furniture</li>
<li><strong>Senior food</strong>. Feed them senior-specific cat food that s=
upports their changing nutritional needs</li>
<li><strong>Stay on top of hydration</strong>. Ensure your cat has access t=
o fresh water at all times. Some older cats may be prone to dehydration, so=
 it's essential to monitor their water intake</li>
<li><strong>Help them with grooming</strong>. Older cats may have difficult=
y grooming themselves, especially if they have arthritis</li>
<li><strong>Keep areas well-lit</strong> to prevent accidents&nbsp;</li>
<li><strong>Mental activity</strong>. Engage your cat in mental and physica=
l activities to keep their mind sharp. Interactive toys, puzzle feeders, an=
d play sessions can be beneficial.</li>
<li><strong>Joint pain</strong>. Consider joint supplements if your cat sho=
ws signs of arthritis or joint stiffness.</li>
<li><strong>Behavior monitoring</strong>. Keep an eye on changes in behavio=
r, appetite, and <a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.com/blog/cat-litter-bo=
x-habits/">litter box habits</a>. Sudden changes may indicate underlying he=
alth issues that require veterinary attention.</li>
<li><strong>Sleeping habits</strong>. <a href=3D"https://www.litter-robot.c=
om/blog/8-tips-aging-cat-sleep-better/">Make sure senior cats get enough sl=
eep</a></li>
</ul>
<p><!-- /wp:list --></p>
<p><!-- wp:heading --></p>
<h2 id=3D"h-love-your-cat-at-any-age">Love your cat at any age&nbsp;</h2>
<p><!-- /wp:heading --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>So, how can you tell how old a cat is? As your cat ages, you will notice=
 changes in their physical appearance and behavior. It is important to tend=
 to those changes and make adjustments to ensure your cat ages comfortably.=
 It might start off as something simple, like making sure they=E2=80=99re g=
etting adequate exercise or providing easier access to their litter box.&nb=
sp;</p>
<p><!-- /wp:paragraph --></p>
<p><!-- wp:paragraph --></p>
<p>As your fur baby ages, their litter habits might change. <a href=3D"http=
s://www.litter-robot.com/litter-robot-4.html">Litter-Robot 4</a> helps redu=
ce cleaning and maintenance, as it is self-cleaning and automatic. It=E2=80=
=99s large enough to accommodate cats of all ages and keeps the bed of litt=
er clean for every visit.&nbsp;</p>
<p><!-- /wp:yoast/faq-block --></p>
